04187nam a22006375i 9781477321317DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212020txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020000758  a97814773213177 a10.7560/3212942doi  a(DE-B1597)587304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1998.3.H84bC48 2020 4aPN1998.3.H84bC48 2020 7aPER0180002bisacsh04a791.430/330922231 aChard, Holly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMainstream Maverick :bJohn Hughes and New Hollywood Cinema /cHolly Chard. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION The Making of "John Hughes" -- tCHAPTER 1. Building a Brand: Universal (1984-1985) -- tCHAPTER 2. Realities and Fantasies of Suburban Adolescence -- tCHAPTER 3. The Creative Producer: Paramount (1985-1987) -- tCHAPTER 4. Gender, Generation, and Coming-of-Age in 1980s America -- tCHAPTER 5. Solid Family Fare: Universal (1988-1990) and Warner Bros. (1987-1993) -- tCHAPTER 6. Pressures of Parenthood and Fantasies of Childhood -- tCHAPTER 7. Family Film Franchises: 20th Century Fox (1989-1997) -- tCHAPTER 8. Slapstick, Sentimentality, and the American Family -- tCONCLUSION Mainstream Maverick? -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1980s and 1990s, John Hughes was one of Hollywood's most reliable hitmakers, churning out beloved teen comedies and family films such as The Breakfast Club and Home Alone, respectively. But was he an artist? Hughes, an adamantly commercial filmmaker who was dismissed by critics, might have laughed at the question. Since his death in 2009, though, he has been memorialized on Oscar night as a key voice of his time. Now the critics lionize him as a stylistic original. Holly Chard traces Hughes's evolution from entertainer to auteur. Studios recognized Hughes's distinctiveness and responded by nurturing his brand. He is therefore a case study in Hollywood's production not only of movies but also of genre and of authorship itself. The films of John Hughes, Chard shows, also owed their success to the marketers who sold them and the audiences who watched. Careful readings of Hughes's cinema reveal both the sources of his iconic status and the imprint on his films of the social, political, economic, and media contexts in which he operated. The first serious treatment of Hughes, Mainstream Maverick elucidates the priorities of the American movie industry in the New Hollywood era and explores how artists not only create but are themselves created.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMotion picture authorship. 0aMotion picture industryxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picture producers and directorsvBiography. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Individual Director (see also BIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Entertainment & Performing Arts).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32129440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477321317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781477321317.jpg  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK